                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Re-examined</hi>). When I say that M. Barnett's expenses were 2,000<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. a year I do not include all the figures which have been read; they are trade expenses.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BESLEY</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">submitted that there was no evidence that the defendant ever received the</hi> 380<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. <hi rend="italic">on 8th October; that, as to the diamonds, they were obtained in France, out of the jurisdiction of this Court; that the</hi>
               </p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187911240074"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">statement that Harris's firm was an old-established one at Lima had not been negatived; that the examination not being put in, there was no evidence I on the tenth count, and that, as to the conspiracy counts, the two brothers were hardly brought together, and there was no evidence of conspiracy at all.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BULWER</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">contended that there was ample evidence of conspiracy as to the "bogus"firm at Lima; that a man might obtain goods in London by I means of a lie told in Paris, the offence being committed where the goods were obtained.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">The Court considered that there was evidence for the Jury on all the I counts except the two relating to Manchester.</hi>
               </p>
